article.description: Coretta Brown came off the bench to score a career-high 22 points as the Indiana Fever defeated the Connecticut Sun 84-74 Friday night for their ninth consecutive victory at home.
article.headline: Rookie leads Indiana to ninth straight home win
article.linkText: Red-hot rookie Brown helps Fever burn Sun
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Coretta Brown is demonstrating she was no throw-in when the Indiana Fever obtained the former North Carolina star in a four-player deal with San Antonio.

Brown came off the bench to score a career-high 22 points, the most by a WNBA rookie this season, as the Fever defeated the Connecticut Sun 84-74 Friday night for their ninth consecutive victory at home.

It was the third consecutive game the 5-foot-9 guard raised her a career high in scoring. She totaled 47 points in the three games, compared with 22 in her first five games.

"She was outstanding," Fever coach Nell Fortner said. "She provided a huge spark for us off the bench."

Brown's production helped Indiana's reserves outscore the Sun's bench 33-10.

"Our bench has made a huge difference with our success this year," Fortner said. "They come in and pick up, we just don't lose anything."

The Fever, who haven't lost at Conseco Fieldhouse since last July 19, built a 48-34 halftime lead with Tamika Catchings contributing 13 of her 22 points.

Brown hit her first seven shots from the field, including four from behind the arc.

"I have been shooting the ball well in practice, and it carried over to the game. That helped me relax," said Brown, who topped her previous single-game high of 13 with 14 points in the first half.

"She's an incredible rookie. What can you say? She's outstanding," said Fortner, who obtained the first-round draft pick as part of a four-player deal that also brought veteran Natalie Williams to Indiana.

"We knew exactly what we were getting," Fortner said of Brown, a two-time All-ACC first-team selection who scored 1,687 points in four seasons with the Tar Heels.

Nykesha Sales led Connecticut with a season-high 26, including 17 in the first half.

Indiana trailed briefly and took the lead for good at 15-14 on a 3-pointer by Catchings.

Connecticut, which came into the game with the WBNA's lowest turnover average (11.9), had 11 in the first half, and Indiana scored 13 points off of turnovers. The Sun finished with 21 turnovers.

The Fever (5-3) pulled away as the Sun (5-4) scored just six points with just one field goal in the final five minutes of the first half. The Sun missed six consecutive shots from the field in that span, ending the streak on a layup by Jessie Hicks with 2.9 seconds left in the half.

A 3-pointer by Sales cut Connecticut's deficit to 33-28 with 5:33 remaining in the period. Indiana responded with eight consecutive points, including five by Williams.

Williams had 18 points and 11 rebounds for the Fever.

Connecticut fell behind by as many as 17 in the second half and cut its deficit to 79-71 with 3:02 to play on a 3-pointer by Adrienne Johnson. Indiana responded with five straight points on two free throws by Catchings, one by Sonja Henning and two by Williams.

"You know going in that Catchings and Williams are going to get their points," Sales said. "Brown was a surprise for us. We were more focused on others. She came in and did a great job."

Shannon Johnson had 16 points for Connecticut, and Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored 11.

The 48 first half-points tied the franchise record for Indiana, which helped itself by hitting on 12-of-16 free throws while shooting 48 percent from the field.
